From 39024a84f120f077fc9a3954bfbc2ea4700d27ec Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vester Imanuel Thacker <v@pgsdf.org>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 09:17:16 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Add and ratify AD-58: Verified System Lifecycle

Establish the system state-transition model and the promotion invariant
forced by the Phase 0.5 drawfs-hang failure: a kernel change made drawfs
hang at framebuffer init, an unverified recovery BE could not escape it,
and the bench was reinstalled, destroying the only environment that
reproduced the bug. Both underlying mistakes were promotions to trust
without verification.

Governing Promotion Rule, set off prominently as the sentence that
governs the document: Awase never promotes a system based on successful
execution; it promotes only after successful verification. It is a
general design rule, not just an installer feature.

State machine Recovery -> Installing -> Unverified -> Verified ->
Released. Verified is an instantaneous promotion gate, not a persistent
state: an environment is Unverified until the act of
verification-and-commit makes it Released, so only three states persist
as Boot Environments. Verification is a distinct act from the change,
generally not performable by the installer.

Boot Environments are the FreeBSD persistence mechanism, not the concept;
the same lifecycle governs package sets, config migrations, schema
changes, and updates, keeping the model portable. Relies on /boot and
/etc being BE-local; any setting that is not is a bug to fix at source.

awase be command (repository-local, dissolving the bootstrap problem):
create --pre-install (Recovery is a named singleton, not timestamped
history), commit (immutable named snapshot of the verified current state,
current BE continues like a git commit; carries provenance metadata
including version, kernel, git commit, verified flag, and verification
method), list (release history showing the current BE as explicitly not
verified), rollback (exactly activate Recovery and reboot, never deletes
the broken BE because it is evidence), delete (explicit only).

install.sh installs software and reports COMPLETED, never SUCCEEDED: it
creates the Recovery BE before any change and instructs the operator to
verify then commit. Implementation deferred to a stable system, where the
first commit fittingly certifies that system.

The scope boundary is stated up front so reviewers evaluate the
architecture, not the implementation.

Status: RATIFIED 2026-06-28 (operator).

Bench: none (design record).
